🔍 Key Insights
Basic subscription plans were the most common, followed closely by Standard and Premium plans.
United States and Canada accounted for the highest proportion of users, followed by the United Kingdom.
The dataset showed an almost equal distribution of male and female subscribers.
Device usage was evenly distributed across smartphones, tablets, laptops, and smart TVs.
Monthly revenue was relatively balanced, with $12/month appearing most frequently among users.

📊 Bivariate Analysis

Relationships between Monthly Revenue and several customer attributes were explored using:

Cross-tabulation
Stacked Bar Charts
Boxplots

Variables analyzed include:

Subscription Type vs Monthly Revenue
Country vs Monthly Revenue
Age vs Monthly Revenue
Gender vs Monthly Revenue

These visualizations helped identify revenue patterns across different customer segments.

📈 Statistical Analysis

The project applies multiple statistical techniques to determine whether customer characteristics significantly influence monthly revenue.

Chi-Square Test of Independence

Performed between:

Subscription Type vs Monthly Revenue
Country vs Monthly Revenue
Gender vs Monthly Revenue
Device vs Monthly Revenue

Purpose:

Determine whether monthly revenue is statistically associated with categorical variables.
Normality Testing

Used:

Shapiro-Wilk Test

Purpose:

Evaluate whether the data follows a normal distribution before selecting appropriate statistical tests.
Homogeneity of Variance

Used:

Levene's Test

Purpose:

Verify whether groups have equal variances.
Non-Parametric Testing

Imported:

Mann–Whitney U Test

This test can be used when normality assumptions are violated to compare distributions between two independent groups.

